Theremon uttered a long, low whistle and sat brooding for several minutes. The men about the table had brought out a multi-chess board and started a six-member game. Moves were made rapidly and in silence. All eyes bent in furious concentration on the board. Theremon watched them intently and then rose and approached Aton, who sat apart in whispered conversation with Sheerin.\par
'Listen,' he said, let's go somewhere where we won't bother the rest of the fellows. I want to ask some questions.'\par
The aged astronomer frowned sourly at him, but Sheerin chirped up, 'Certainly. It will do me good to talk. It always does. Aton was telling me about your ideas concerning world reaction to a failure of the prediction -- and I agree with you. I read your column pretty regularly, by the way, and as a general thing I like your views.'\par
'Please, Sheerin,' growled Aton.\par
'Eh? Oh, all right. We'll go into the next room. It has softer chairs, anyway.'\par
There were softer chairs in the next room. There were also thick red curtains on the windows and a maroon carpet on the floor. With the bricky light of Beta pouring in, the general effect was one of dried blood.\par
Theremon shuddered. 'Say, I'd give ten credits for a decent dose of white light for just a second. I wish Gamma or Delta were in the sky.'\par
'What are your questions?' asked Aton. 'Please remember that our time is limited. In a little over an hour and a quarter we're going upstairs, and after that there will be no time for talk.'\par
'Well, here it is.' Theremon leaned back and folded his hands on his chest. 'You people seem so all-fired serious about this that I'm beginning to believe you. Would you mind explaining what it's all about?'\par
Aton exploded, 'Do you mean to sit there and tell me that you've been bombarding us with ridicule without even finding out what we've been trying to say?'\par
The columnist grinned sheepishly. 'It's not that bad, sir. I've got the general idea. You say there is going to be a world-wide Darkness in a few hours and that all mankind will go violently insane. What I want now is the science behind it.'\par
'No, you don't. No, you don't,' broke in Sheerin. 'If you ask Aton for that -- supposing him to be in the mood to answer at all -- he'll trot out pages of figures and volumes of graphs. You won't make head or tail of it. Now if you were to ask me, I could give you the layman's standpoint.'\par
'All right; I ask you.'\par
'Then first I'd like a drink.' He rubbed his hands and looked at Aton.\par
'Water?' grunted Aton.\par
'Don't be silly!'\par
'Don't you be silly. No alcohol today. It would be too easy to get my men drunk. I can't afford to tempt them.'\par
The psychologist grumbled wordlessly. He turned to Theremon, impaled him with his sharp eyes, and began.\par
'You realize, of course, that the history of civilization on Lagash displays a cyclic character -- but I mean cyclic!'\par
'I know,' replied Theremon cautiously, 'that that is the current archaeological theory. Has it been accepted as a fact?'\par
